<paragraph xmlns:gate="http://www.gate.ac.uk" gate:gateId="0" gate:annotMaxId="261">Abraham, Max, German publisher; <Event_Birth gate:gateId="259" RE="June 3, 1831" Pred="birth" Pred-tyoe="time"><Birth gate:gateId="255" predict="birth">b.</Birth> Danzig, <Date gate:gateId="212" rule1="DateNameRev" kind="date" rule2="DateOnlyFinal">June 3, 1831</Date></Event_Birth>; <Event_Birth gate:gateId="260" RE="Dec. 8, 1900" Pred="death" Pred-tyoe="time"><Death gate:gateId="256" predict="death">d.</Death> <Location gate:gateId="213" rule1="Location1" locType="city" rule2="LocFinal">Leipzig</Location>, <Date gate:gateId="214" rule1="DateNameRev" kind="date" rule2="DateOnlyFinal">Dec. 8, 1900</Date></Event_Birth>. He became a partner in G. F. Peters&apos; &apos;Bureau de Musique&apos; in <Date gate:gateId="216" rule1="YearContext1" kind="date" rule2="DateOnlyFinal">1863</Date>, and sole proprietor in <Date gate:gateId="217" rule1="YearContext1" kind="date" rule2="DateOnlyFinal">1880</Date>. On <Date gate:gateId="218" rule1="DateNameRev" kind="date" rule2="DateOnlyFinal">Jan. 1, 1894</Date>, his nephew, Heinrich Hinrichsen, of <Location gate:gateId="220" rule1="Location1" locType="city" rule2="LocFinal">Hamburg</Location>, entered the firm and, upon Abraham&apos;s death, became its head. The famous &apos;Edition Peters&apos; was inaugurated by Abraham. </paragraph>